-- Regression test for issue #905: the EVENT type name used to be shadowed by
-- its own term constructor (the un-renamed `event` builtin surfaces, uppercased,
-- as "EVENT" -- the very name the `eventC` constructor is renamed to). As two
-- separate initialEnvironment entries the type was silently dropped, so an
-- event-typed signature like `GIVEN e IS AN EVENT ...` was unresolvable, and as
-- a side effect EVENT was excluded from exhaustiveness checking.
--
-- Both are fixed now: the signature below names the EVENT type, and the
-- single-constructor CONSIDER is (correctly) accepted as exhaustive -- EVENT has
-- exactly one constructor, so one `WHEN EVENT ...` arm covers it.
DECLARE Party IS ONE OF alice, bob
DECLARE Act IS ONE OF ping, pong

GIVEN e IS AN EVENT Party Act
GIVETH A Party
whoActed e MEANS
  CONSIDER e
  WHEN EVENT p a n THEN p

GIVEN e IS AN EVENT Party Act
GIVETH A NUMBER
whenActed e MEANS
  CONSIDER e
  WHEN EVENT p a n THEN n

#EVAL whoActed (EVENT alice ping 5)   -- expect alice
#EVAL whenActed (EVENT bob pong 42)   -- expect 42
